            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Caleb Sharma\u2019s name hints at the two worlds of his childhood. Born in central Illinois to a reserved Indian engineer father and a free-spirited White mother who taught community ceramics, Caleb grew up navigating the space between pragmatism and artistry. He was the quiet kid who preferred the high school auditorium to the football field, finding solace in the tangible magic of stagecraft. He could spend hours on a ladder, focusing a single beam of light until it created the perfect mood.\n\nThis passion led him to a state university's theater arts program, but he found himself stifled by academic theory. The real education was in the student-run black box theater. During his sophomore year, a touring production came through town, and their lighting designer, a grizzled veteran, took a liking to Caleb\u2019s work ethic. He offered him a spot as a roadie. It was a pivotal moment: the diploma or the real world. Caleb dropped out and never looked back, learning his craft in dusty theaters across the country.\n\nHe landed in San Francisco in the late \u201890s, drawn by its reputation for experimental and unapologetic art. He spent years hustling, taking any gig he could find, from tiny Mission District storefront theaters to corporate events. Slowly, he built a reputation for being reliable, creative, and calm under pressure. Now, at 49, he's a respected lighting designer for several mid-size Bay Area companies.\n\nHis life is a well-worn groove. His 3.5-mile bike ride from his rent-controlled apartment in the Lower Haight to the theaters around the Tenderloin and SoMa is a daily ritual, a mental transition from his quiet, book-filled home to the controlled chaos of production. His social life is inseparable from his work\u2014post-show drinks with cast and crew are his primary connection. He\u2019s had relationships, but his truest partner has always been the work. His modest income requires a careful budget, but he values his artistic freedom over wealth. Caleb\u2019s dream is no longer fame, but mastery. He hopes to one day design a single, perfect show that audiences will remember for its light, and to mentor a new generation before the physical demands of the job catch up to him."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 16, alone in the high school auditorium after midnight, prepping for *Our Town*. He spent an hour on a ladder, minutely adjusting a single Fresnel spotlight on the empty stage. When he finally clicked it on, the beam cut through the darkness, creating a perfect, lonely pool of light where Emily would stand. In the humming silence, he felt a power that was both creative and absolute\u2014the god-like ability to shape not just light, but feeling itself. It was the moment his hobby became a calling.\n\n2.\nHe can still smell the stale coffee and dust of the university\u2019s black box theater. He was 19. The touring lighting designer, a gruff man named Sal, watched him work and then offered him a job as a roadie. \"The bus leaves at dawn. You in?\" Caleb felt the tectonic plates of his life shift. His father\u2019s pragmatism screamed \"diploma,\" but his mother\u2019s spirit urged him toward the raw, dusty reality of the road. Saying \"yes\" was the first decision he ever made that felt entirely his own.\n\n3.\nSan Francisco, 2001. A tiny, sweltering storefront theater in the Mission. Mid-performance, a crucial circuit blew, plunging half the stage into darkness. While the actors vamped, Caleb, drenched in sweat, calmly spliced cables in a dark corner, bypassing the fried board. He got the lights back on just in time for the climactic monologue. The director\u2019s exhausted, grateful nod after the show felt more valuable than any paycheck. That night, he learned that his calm was a currency more reliable than cash.\n\n4.\nHe remembers the argument with Sarah in his Lower Haight apartment, around his late thirties. She was pleading with him to come to her sister's wedding in Sonoma. But he was in tech week, obsessed with achieving the precise, watery blue light for a dream sequence. He recalls staring at the colored gel in his hand, feeling its texture, more real to him than her tearful request. He chose the light. The relationship ended soon after, cementing the quiet, solitary shape of his life.\n\n5.\nJust last year, during a load-in, he watched a new intern, a quiet kid barely 20, struggle to focus an old Leko. Without a word, Caleb climbed the ladder and showed her the trick to sharpening the beam's edge. He saw the flash of understanding and delight in her eyes\u2014the same magic he\u2019d felt at 16. It wasn't about being the master anymore. It was the first time he truly felt the deep, satisfying pull of passing the craft on, of ensuring the light wouldn\u2019t go out."
